zebo platform-simulated\nenvironments, achieving a significantly larger explored area, with the average\ndistance and time traveled being reduced. Moreover, the operated proposed\nmethod on an author-built 2D robot exploring the entire natural environment\nconfirms that the method is effective and applicable in real-world scenarios.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 8 May 2023 09:34:55 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-05-09"}
{"id":"2305.04577","submitter":"Marwan Mostafa","authors":"Marwan Mostafa, Davood Babazadeh, Christian Becker","title":"Strategic Decision Making in the Planning of Integrated Multi-energy\n  Networks Under Uncertainty","comments":"Submitted to IEEE PES ISGT 2023","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"eess.SY cs.SY","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  This paper proposes a framework for the integrated planning of multi-energy\nnetworks, including electricity and district heating systems, to optimize the\nuse of different energy carriers and reduce the carbon footprint of energy\nsystems. Integrating multiple energy carriers in the planning of distribution\nnetworks presents new challenges, including uncertainties in demand prediction,\nenergy prices, and renewable energy availability. In response to these\nchallenges, we propose an approach that aims to aid strategic decision-making\nin a new planning process for integrated multi-energy networks using robust\noptimization. The uncertainty in energy prices is modeled using interval\nuncertainty with a proportional deviation. This allows network operators and\nregulators to forecast the likely decision to be made by the household customer\nto choose one heating technology that minimizes a cost function subject to\nvarious constraints while ensuring robustness against the uncertainty in energy\nprices. The results show that the expansion of the district heating\ninfrastructure results in the lowest total economic costs in most cases and\ncells. The results also show that an increase in the size of the uncertainty\nsets causes an increase in the total economic costs of heating. The paper\nconcludes with a discussion of future directions to expand this approach to\nmodel more uncertain parameters.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 8 May 2023 09:35:22 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-05-09"}
