of the Cayley graph\n$\\Gamma(G,A).$ Then, $\\Gamma_n(G,A)$ and $\\mathsf{G}(n,1/2)$ are statistically\nindistinguishable with high probability over $A$ if and only if $\\log|G|\\gtrsim\nn.$ However, low-degree polynomial tests fail to distinguish $\\Gamma_n(G,A)$\nand $\\mathsf{G}(n,1/2)$ with high probability over $A$ when $\\log\n|G|=\\log^{\\Omega(1)}n.$\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 8 May 2023 15:55:33 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 9 May 2023 00:53:32 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-05-10"}
